07791nam a22008055i 9780822380221DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20002000ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223802217 a10.1515/97808223802212doi  a(DE-B1597)553105  a(OCoLC)870347750  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS779.23b.P675 2000 7aHIS0080002bisacsh00aPostmodernism and China /cArif Dirlik, Xudong Zhang. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b16 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Postmodernism and China -- tI . mapping the postmodern -- t1. The Mapping of Chinese Postmodernity -- t2. On Be(ij)ing in theWorld: ''Postmodernism,'' ''Globalization,'' and the Making of Transnational Space in China -- t3. Postmodern Literary Discourse and Contemporary Public Culture in Taiwan -- t4. Hong Kong, China, and the Question of Postcoloniality -- tII . cultural politics -- t5. Popular Culture and the Culture of the Masses in Contemporary China -- t6. Global POSTmodernIZATION: The Intellectual, the Artist, and China's Condition -- t7. Becoming Cyborgian: Postmodernism and Nationalism in Contemporary Taiwan -- tIII . cultural studies -- t8. Imagined Nostalgia -- t9. The Mysterious Other: Postpolitics in Chinese Film -- t10. ''Let Him Fucking See the Green Smoke Beneath My Groin'': The Mythology of Chinese Rock -- t11. Borrowed Modernity: History and the Subject in A Borrowed Life -- t12. Postmodernism and Hong Kong Cinema -- tIV .literary interventions -- t13. Postmodernism and Chinese Novels of the Nineties -- t14. Women and the Discourse of Desire in Postrevolutionary China: The Awkward Postmodernism of Chen Ran -- t15. Melancholy against the Grain: Approaching Postmodernity inWang Anyi's Tales of Sorrow -- t16. Whence and Whither the Postmodern/Post-Mao-Deng: Historical Subjectivity and Literary Subjectivity in Modern China -- tEpilogue: Postmodernism and Postsocialist Society- Historicizing the Present -- tSelected Glossary of Terms and Titles -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew countries have been so transformed in recent decades as China. With a dynamically growing economy and a rapidly changing social structure, China challenges the West to understand the nature of its modernization. Using postmodernism as both a global frame of periodization and a way to break free from the rigid ideology of westernization as modernity, this volume's diverse group of contributors argues that the Chinese experience is crucial for understanding postmodernism.Collectively, these essays question the implications of specific phenomena, like literature, architecture, rock music, and film, in a postsocialist society. Some essays address China's complicity in-as well as its resistance to-the culture of global capitalism. Others evaluate the impact of efforts to redefine national culture in terms of enhanced freedoms and expressions of the imagination in everyday life. Still others discuss the general relaxation of political society in post-Mao China, the emergence of the market and its consumer mass culture, and the fashion and discourse of nostalgia. The contributors make a clear case for both the historical uniqueness of Chinese postmodernism and the need to understand its specificity in order to fully grasp the condition of postmodernity worldwide. Although the focus is on mainland China, the volume also includes important observations on social and cultural realities in Hong Kong and Taiwan, whose postmodernity has so far been confined-in both Chinese and English-speaking worlds-to their economic and consumer activities instead of their political and cultural dynamism.First published as a special issue of boundary 2, Postmodernism and China includes seven new essays. By juxtaposing postmodernism with postsocialism and by analyzing China as a producer and not merely a consumer of the culture of the postmodern, it will contribute to critical discourses on globalism, modernity, and political economics, as well as to cultural and Asian studies.Contributors. Evans Chan, Arif Dirlik, Dai Jinhua, Liu Kang, Anthony D. King, Jeroen de Kloet, Abidin Kusno, Wendy Larson, Chaoyang Liao, Ping-hui Liao, Sebastian Hsien-hao Liao, Sheldon Hsiao-peng Lu, Wang Ning, Xiaobing Tang, Xiaoying Wang, Chen Xiaoming, Xiaobin Yang, Zhang Yiwu, Xudong Zhang  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aPopular culturezChina. 0aPostmodernismzChina. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aKusno, Abidin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirlik, Arif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiao, Chao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aXiaoming, Chen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJinhua, Dai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirlik, Arif, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKloet, Jeroen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Anthony D.1 aKusno, Abidin1 aLiao, Ping-Hui1 aKang, Liu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNing, Wang1 aLiao, Ping, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiao, Sebastian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLu, Sheldon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNing, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarson, Wendy, 